', "Today something different from the usual format. That's what I love of London, the mix of old architecture steps away from modern buildings, the City of London is full sights and corners like this one in St Helen's Square. 
The St. Andrew Undershaft church is one of the few rare churches built around the 15th century which has survived both the Great Fire of London in the 17th century and the Blitz bombing during the second World War. The Church has been partially restored after the IRA's bombings in the 90s.

In the background, the skyscraper named The Scalpel and a reflection of the 30 St Mary Axe, commonly known as the Gherkin Tower because apparently Londoners like to nickname buildings by their look and shape 🥒

", 'Yesterday, Ian had an issue with his insulin pump, leading to him having no insulin in his body for an extended period of time, leading to diabetic ketoacidosis. 
This is a scary moment for us, as it was this issue that sent him into the hospital in the first place, when he was 5 years old, before we knew he was diabetic at all. His sister Anika won a green hippo for him at a Village Inn crane machine during his first hospital stay, and she gave it to him then. Today, she brought it back to him. 
This time was one hundred percent different from last time, with the notable exception that it still scared the hell out of me. We knew what to expect, his mother immediately administered insulin and took him to the ER. He will be getting out today, but I'll never forget his description of DKA as feeling like "my blood was on fire." Happy to have to him safe, and hoping it never happens again.

I'm working on that girl in the mirror. Working on making changes. Also, working on loving myself right where I am. I'm certain that I am where I am supposed to be right now. AND, I know that I have the courage and power to change what needs to be shifted to be where I should be in the future.
", 'The last 5 months have been a nightmare and a gift.

In one way I am absolutely isolated in my home or car from doing anything. Having a daughter with an immunodeficiency, CVID, has kept me running scared. A regular germ can send her spiraling down hill fast and to the hospital. A covid infection would be devastating. My boy,  Ryan, and his ultra rare genetic syndrome & autism just can't handle an illness the powers of the coronavirus. And both boys have celiac disease, an autoimmune disease, and many other food and environmental allergies. To top it off, Ryan simply can't/won't wear a mask. Pretty much leaves us to drives in the country and lots of home time.

The blessings come in the time gifted to us with no appointments and no buildings we can enter. We have spent so many hours out exploring our area. State parks, new lakes, farm areas, Amish Country, Sonic happy hours, Chipotlé to go and so much more. The hours we have spent out in nature this summer are priceless.  This social isolation from others has truly been a gift. We have laughed more and gotten dirtier than ever before. And we rescued sister cats.

As school looms close, I am trying to make sure we don't loose this free spirited time we have found to just be "us".

Have you been blessed by the slower pace of isolation?
', "My boy caught his very first fish today.

Just a mom brag. That's all.  He was so excited.

He named him Jerry.
", "To the boy they said wasn't going to make it....I'm so proud of you. You are starting your second half of high school. You amaze me at every turn. Your light shines bright in every situation. You fight so hard to be you. And I love the you that you are.

To the doctors that told me my son would not make it.....you were so very wrong! He is rocking this life in ways you never could have imagined!! You failed to see the magic in our team back then. You can't miss it now.
", '8 weeks ago we rescued 2 little sisters from an Amish farm. I realized I never introduced them to you formally. (They play in my stories almost daily) On the left is Cheddar. On the right is Carmelita (Carmel for short). They are the sweetest to each other and to us. Constantly playing and running through the house. Always purring and knocking everything over. We love them so very much. They sure make staying home more fun.
', 'My mini-me. So in love with this boy!!
', "This is me taking in this beautiful world.

Tonight we are waiting for election results. I am reminding myself that whoever wins, it will not change me. It will not change natures beauty. It can't stifle my love for my family. It will not keep me from seeing the good in everything and everyone around me. It will not discourage me from putting my best out there.

I will continue to see the beauty in the world and I hope you do too.
", "2020 has been rough for so many of us. As Thanksgiving approaches this week I want to challenge you to look for the little things that bring you joy.

Listen for the bark of your neighbor's dog that reminds you that you aren't alone. Cook something you love to eat, have seconds and don't count the calories. One meal won't derail your diet. Chat with your distant family, on the phone or maybe zoom, and listen to the goofy stories carefully. Purposefully find the joy!!

This year I'm having the usual small Thanksgiving with just who live here in my home. And I will eat that second helping, be extra goofy and make the best of this weird year.

Find your joy.
", "My baby is 14!! I still can't believe how fast time flies. I love you little dude!!
", 'You caught me.  I've been struggling. This winter has been taking me down hard. Harder than I imagined it could.

Cyber-schooling a special needs child is so much harder than I thought it would be. Getting on Zoom 27 times a week, at 30 minutes each, is wearing me out. I have to be present, engaged, interactive AND getting Ryan to do the same. I'm his voice for the speech therapist, hands for the physical therapist, eyes for the vision therapist, hands for the occupational therapist and his everything for his core subjects. His teachers are incredible. Simple fact is.....they aren't here. They are magical directors but ultimately the work falls on me. I'm drowning. Breakfast, lunch, dinner, snacks. All fed to him one piece at a time. He isn't potty trained. Doesn't have the ability yet. It's a lot to manage.

I'm working on finding my way out. And this isn't a complaint. I'm sure most of you have experienced similar things this year. Just acknowledging that it's kicking my tail.

 My 16 year old "toddler" is fighting so hard every day to grow and learn and I am doing everything I can to help him blossom. It's just hard work. He's TOTALLY WORTH IT!!
', 'The snow was absolutely beautiful today.
', 'Winter is almost over. Hints of Spring are starting. The sun is out. The temps are rising. My smile is returning. My hope is increasing. Bring on the warm weather.
']

', 'At about 8:30 this morning, my kitty Enid died at our vet. She would have been 12 in a few months. On some level we'd been preparing for this for a while--she'd been diagnosed with kidney failure a little over a year ago--but these final few days, when things took a sudden turn, were still so shocking and unexpected. I'm thankful she's no longer struggling, and that I was with her in the last moments, scratching her cheek and head in the way only I knew how.

Over this last decade, she was truly MY kitty. When I worked overseas for a while I left her with my folks for about three months. The first morning I was back she immediately jumped into my lap and snuggled up against me, something my parents said had never happened in her time there. Beth can attest to the numerous times Enid would yowl with loneliness when I was gone, but would completely ignore her when Beth would call "hey, I'm right here!" There was only one person she truly wanted, and I'm glad I got to feel her soft fur one last time this morning.

["I had another great week of work in Vancouver. It's always a rewarding trip, but my friends @shahedkh & @marjanjay made it extra bonus fun by taking me up to Whistler for the day.

But I just can't wait to get back to the fam tomorrow!
", "With a last minute VRBO booking, we spent a tasty little treat of a weekend in the mountain town of Salida, CO. Somehow we'd never spent any time there, but we now know we'll be back.

It's right along the Arkansas River, which means it's a big rafting and fly fishing town. The town itself is full of art galleries, consignment stores, restaurants, and bike shops; aka very cool.
", 'Commuting home from work and dinner with these two sure is hilarious!
', 'I agree, little man: that bunny is freaky big and why is he wearing a bow tie?
', "#vanlife is officially for sale!
-
That's right. We've made the call to part ways with our beloved Stella so that we can make our plans for another adventuremobile a reality.
-
This van is road ready and itching to get after that next adventure. We've had two VW specific shops do everything they can think of to make sure she's starting out strong for the next owner. The second shop said, “This really doesn't need a tune up.” So... looking good, I'd say.
-
Full description of all upgrades, photos, and a non-quick-edit-like-a-crazy-person version of this same video are at http://bit.ly/stella-for-sale (link in profile).
", "“How's it going, buddy?”
“Djeahhhh”
", 'Headed to the mountains for a long weekend of family camping and fishing. Likely our last adventure in Stella. 😢
', "Today's (mis)adventure took us along Shelf Road, which is an historic wagon road to gold mines. This was taken from a wide spot in the road. Otherwise it's pretty much 45 minutes of single lane dirt trail with the downhill side making the shotgun rider (@bcrest) nice and nervous. “4wd and high clearance vehicles only”, so you know we fit right in.
", 'Whistle while you work 😙
', "This rad little dude is a year and a half old today. It's wild to think how much he's changed and how much he's changed us in such a short amount of time. 
He makes us laugh and smile and enjoy the little moments every day. Seeing him figure things out on his own and his personality come through is, to put it lightly, insanely gratifying.

Thanks for letting me be your dad, little man!
", 'I went for a morning spin through an area that had burned just a month or two ago. Super lush and barely any remaining brush.
', 'Totes in Vancouver right now.
', 'I didn't think sharing life skills would start so early, but this little guy is just a sponge. While he may not be roasting dogs or s'mores in the immediate future, I can already tell his brain is taking notes and picking up on hundreds of little things every day. Like how storing your bib in the back pocket of your jeans gets more style points. And saying "Wooow" to anything remotely cool instantly makes it cooler for everyone. 
I didn't know what to expect as a dad, but it's hella fun right now. Thanks dude!
', "My best friend since we were 2.5 years old, Joel (@vingerjoel), got married over the weekend just outside of Jackson, Wyoming.

The weekend and all the festivities felt more like a summer camp than a wedding. It was so much fun to see old roommates and friends come together and act like nothing has changed—except for there being kids and more spouses to hang with.

The crew at this wedding was one of a kind. So many adventurers and people full of life. It felt like half of them were either heading to South America or weren't sure where they'd be off to after the wedding. Kindred spirits from the various walks of Joel and Katy's lives, but all connected through them and their contagious joy for life. Needless to say, we had a blast. And the dancing. Oh the dancing. Nary a wallflower was found in the barn that night.
", 'Flying the stars and stripes. 🇺🇸
', 'Sight fishing.
', '#Goodnight moon.

Goodnight trees and goodnight hammock.
Goodnight Lego Head of Zorro made by the shapes of those things we just said “Goodnight” to.
Goodnight, you.
', "Little man's first taste of Little Man ice cream. 🍦
", 'We took our final camping trip in Stella this weekend. It was bittersweet, but we made the most of it with hiking, boating, swimming, and playing in puddles.

', 'So cool! #eclipse

', 'Another incredible week in the books here in Vancouver—capped off by taking my UX team kayaking yesterday afternoon.
', 'A little fishing with my little man. His stick caught just as many trout as my tenkara rod. At least the photo is a keeper.

Thanks @clairespragoo!

', 'And we’re off!
-
The new van conversion project is under way and off to a quick start (with lots of help). New venting side windows, a ceiling vent/van, and insulation were installed last week by @vanlifecustoms.
-
Factory floor removed and a new subfloor cut to template by my dad, Arlo, and yours truly over the weekend. (It was ridiculously fun to build with them.)
-
Auxiliary electrical system is going in over the next week or so (also by Vanlife Customs). -
And then it’ll likely be much slower progress for the other interior stuff, but it’s feeling great so far.
', 'Welp, that day was fun as hell. We arrived in London yesterday and managed to catch a Chelsea match today. The stadium experience was all I hoped it’d be. We then explored Chelsea and Piccadilly Circus with great food and a comedy club to finish the day. 🙌🙌
', 'Banksy + Basquiat + Keith Haring
—
This piece, and another just across the street, is up between the Underground station and the venue for the design leadership conference I’ve been attending this week (more on that later). Pretty damn cool to see this kind of thing in person.
', 'Become a better design leader. That’s the reason I came to London; to attend a design conference unlike any I’ve been to before. It was, to put it lightly, incredible.
-
Attendees and speakers came from around the world and from organizations huge (GE, IBM, Spotify, etc.) and small (agencies, 5 person startups, etc). No matter the size of their organization or team, most were struggling with similar things, albeit at different scales. Things like: team structure, stakeholder management, do I even know what I’m doing, taking advantage of design’s relatively new seat at the table, etc.
-
It was a bit of a kumbaya “We’re all figuring out the same shit as we go” time (which is insanely reassuring), but also a lot of “MBA for Design” type sessions that I know will help me and my team do more meaningful work (that stuff will take me quite a while to process).
-
Photo: Baker Street tube station; my departure point each morning to get to the conference.
-
#journal #design
', 'All fired up for Halloween!
', 'I facilitated our first ever design sprint* this week at @aclspirit. It was an awesome experience with a great crew of collaborators. Lots of learning as we went, and lots of great ideas were generated for future design sprints. I’m excited to do the next one
-
*(A process created by Google Ventures for quickly working toward solutions to big challenges).
', 'The best homecoming! AND the best little helper (installing the van subfloor and making guacamole).
', 'Shou sugi-ban
-
(4 photos; swipe) The aesthetic and function of Japanese-style charred wood has always intrigued me. If you’re not familiar, it’s worth checking out some of the amazing cabins built with this blackened wood.
-
I’m liking the idea of doing the walls of our #sprinterconversion in this style. With the help of my buddy @chrisgregori (who also helped me massively by talking through my build plans and figuring out the order to do things; which is far more complicated than I’d imagined), we charred some pine planks today as a test. After brushing and washing with water, they looked damn cool.
-
I don’t want the interior to feel too dark though, so we explored the idea of doing a whitewash over the charred wood. Yeah, it’s pretty rad. I could see a mix of the two looking fresh. But that’ll have to wait for @bcrest and Arlo to return home and give the 👍 or 👎.
-

', 'When I lived in DC, every year there was a day I referred to as Tom Petty Day. It was a different day every year, and you never knew when it would be, but you know when it arrived — a warm, sunny spring day when you first felt that the weather had turned a corner from sometimes warm/sometimes cold to consistently warm. In the sun and the warmth I’d realize Tom Petty Day was upon us, open the windows, hit play on Petty’s greatest hits CD and make things official with the first few notes of American Girl. I loved Tom Petty Day.
.
I was sad when I realized there is no Tom Petty Day in San Francisco; the weather just isn’t consistent or predictable enough; you never feel like the sun and warmth will stay for a more than a few days, certainly not for months. And so now I celebrate the occasional Tom Petty One Desperate Moment, when the weather is spectacular and the fog lifts, outside and in.
.
*well she was an American girl, raised on promises ....*
.
(Why Tom Petty? ‘Cause I nearly wore that CD out spring semester freshman year of college, and as a result associate it strongly with a bright, warm DC spring day. Nothing more to it than that. Well, that and the fact that Tom Petty was awesome.)

', 'APS is Arizona’s largest utility. It has a monopoly over the electricity business in much of the state. A monopoly over something everyone *has* to buy is a pretty good thing to have, if you’re into making money. And APS is *very* into making money. Half a *billion* dollars in profit last year alone.
...
But APS is never satisfied; not with hundreds of millions in profits. CEO Don Brandt personally took home millions. All for selling something people could only buy from them — and that they *had* to buy.
... It gets hot in the summer in Arizona. Like, 115 degrees hot, daily, for long stretches. In weather like that, you need air conditioning, you need fans — you need electricity. Or you die. ...
APS didn’t *need* the fifty bucks or so that 72-year-old Stephanie Pullman was a few days late in paying when APS decided to cut off her electricity on a 107 degree day. But APS sure *wanted* it.
...
A week later the county sheriff’s office found Stephanie in her home, dead of environmental heat exposure, her body already decomposing.
...
This will become more common, if we let it. Climate change will make hot days like that more common. An economy rigged to allow wealthy corporations to do whatever they want in the name of making a buck will lead to more millionaires like Don Brandt, too busy counting their cash to give a damn who dies when their electricity gets shut off. ...
If we let it.

Saunders’ Pegu Club in New York announced a few weeks ago that it will not re-open.
.
